{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_delta","contentIndex":1,"delta":"\"}","partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We need to decide vote based on record. The prompt includes arguments from both sides. We need to determine if proposition is demonstrated (true) or not demonstrated.\n\nWe must consider preponderance of evidence. The record shows a court unsealed a note described as alleged suicide note, and news reports before deadline reported it as such, but with caveats: unsiged, not authenticated, DOJ never had it, and brother claims forgery.\n\nWe need to decide which side more likely. The rule requires \"credibly reported\" that the note was written by Epstein and intended as suicide note/final message. The reports do say \"alleged\" and \"purported\", but they report it as such. Is that sufficient credibility? The defense argues that \"credibly reported\" still requires credible reporting of authorship and intent. The reports indicate uncertainty and do not verify authorship. However they are credible sources (Guardian, AP) reporting that a note was unsealed and described as alleged note. Does that meet \"credibly reported to have been written by Epstein\"? Probably borderline. The presence of explicit statements of uncertainty may reduce credibility. The defense also has Business Insider article with brother claiming forgery. That is also credible source.\n\nGiven preponderance needed, weigh evidence: plaintiff has court order, two credible reports, note content implying suicide. Defense has doubts, lack of authentication, no signature, DOJ never saw it, brother says forgery. The question: more likely than not that the note was credibly reported as written by Epstein and intended as suicide note. The reports are qualified but still report it as alleged note. I think under \"credibly reported\" standard, the reports are credible even though they note uncertainty. The preponderance may favor plaintiff? But defense's points about authenticity are substantial. However the rule specifically says \"credibly reported\" not necessarily verified. Since reports state \"alleged\" and \"purported\", is that still credible reporting? Likely yes. The market rule expects that. So vote \"demonstrated\".\n\nWe'll submit vote \"demonstrated\" with brief rationale.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-9e5887796ce5ca75","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Court order unsealed a note described as a purported Epstein suicide note and credible pre‑deadline reports (Guardian, AP) identified it as such, satisfying the preponderance standard despite unresolved authentication.\"}"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\":\"aar_submit_council_vote\",\"args\":\"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Court order unsealed a note described as a purported Epstein suicide note and credible pre‑deadline reports (Guardian, AP) identified it as such, satisfying the preponderance standard despite unresolved authentication.\\\"}\"}","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782797493544,"responseId":"gen-1782797493-CvJHVYfHCXUhwvVdRSms"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We need to decide vote based on record. The prompt includes arguments from both sides. We need to determine if proposition is demonstrated (true) or not demonstrated.\n\nWe must consider preponderance of evidence. The record shows a court unsealed a note described as alleged suicide note, and news reports before deadline reported it as such, but with caveats: unsiged, not authenticated, DOJ never had it, and brother claims forgery.\n\nWe need to decide which side more likely. The rule requires \"credibly reported\" that the note was written by Epstein and intended as suicide note/final message. The reports do say \"alleged\" and \"purported\", but they report it as such. Is that sufficient credibility? The defense argues that \"credibly reported\" still requires credible reporting of authorship and intent. The reports indicate uncertainty and do not verify authorship. However they are credible sources (Guardian, AP) reporting that a note was unsealed and described as alleged note. Does that meet \"credibly reported to have been written by Epstein\"? Probably borderline. The presence of explicit statements of uncertainty may reduce credibility. The defense also has Business Insider article with brother claiming forgery. That is also credible source.\n\nGiven preponderance needed, weigh evidence: plaintiff has court order, two credible reports, note content implying suicide. Defense has doubts, lack of authentication, no signature, DOJ never saw it, brother says forgery. The question: more likely than not that the note was credibly reported as written by Epstein and intended as suicide note. The reports are qualified but still report it as alleged note. I think under \"credibly reported\" standard, the reports are credible even though they note uncertainty. The preponderance may favor plaintiff? But defense's points about authenticity are substantial. However the rule specifically says \"credibly reported\" not necessarily verified. Since reports state \"alleged\" and \"purported\", is that still credible reporting? Likely yes. The market rule expects that. So vote \"demonstrated\".\n\nWe'll submit vote \"demonstrated\" with brief rationale.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-9e5887796ce5ca75","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Court order unsealed a note described as a purported Epstein suicide note and credible pre‑deadline reports (Guardian, AP) identified it as such, satisfying the preponderance standard despite unresolved authentication.\"}"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\":\"aar_submit_council_vote\",\"args\":\"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Court order unsealed a note described as a purported Epstein suicide note and credible pre‑deadline reports (Guardian, AP) identified it as such, satisfying the preponderance standard despite unresolved authentication.\\\"}\"}","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782797493544,"responseId":"gen-1782797493-CvJHVYfHCXUhwvVdRSms"}}
